st.schema.json:496:        \"morphology_class\"\nschemas/milestone_1_experiment_manifest.schema.json:502:        \"morphology_class\": {\nschemas/milestone_1_experiment_manifest.schema.json:512:        \"default_morphology_class\": {\nmanifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml:6:circuit_name: t4_t5_motion_patch\nmanifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml:7:model_scope: T4/T5 carry morphology-resolved surface dynamics; upstream and downstream partners remain matched reduced or point models.\nmanifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml:35:notes: Milestone 1 demo manifest for the same circuit, same simple moving-edge stimulus, matched readout, intact-versus-shuffled topology ablation, and explicit P0/P1 baseline challenge. Numeric pass thresholds remain intentionally unspecified at design-lock time.\nmanifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml:40:  - same_circuit_same_stimulus\nmanifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml:46:    morphology_condition: intact_synapse_landing_geometry\nmanifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml:48:    notes: Canonical point baseline on the matched circuit and shared readout.\nmanifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml:56:    morphology_condition: intact_synapse_landing_geometry\nmanifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml:58:    notes: Surface-wave condition with distributed morphology-bound state on T4/T5 only.\nmanifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml:66:    morphology_condition: shuffled_synapse_landing_geometry\nmanifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml:76:    morphology_condition: shuffled_synapse_landing_geometry\nmanifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml:86:    morphology_condition: intact_synapse_landing_geometry\nmanifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml:96:    morphology_condition: shuffled_synapse_landing_geometry\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:18:  locked_hypothesis: \"Morphology-resolved surface dynamics constitute an additional intraneuronal computational degree of freedom, capable of shaping circuit input-output transformations through distributed spatiotemporal state on neuronal structure.\"\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:19:  operational_claim: \"In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.\"\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:39:      statement: Geometry dependence through topology or morphology perturbation.\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:48:    description: Detect a nonzero shared-output effect centered on null-direction suppression when morphology-bound surface dynamics are present.\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:59:      - same circuit\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:65:    notes: Optimize Milestone 1 around null-direction suppression rather than headline task accuracy.\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:78:      - same circuit\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:137:      - same circuit\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:150:      description: Show point baseline and surface-wave model side by side on the same T4/T5-centered circuit.\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:168:    description: Side-by-side view of scalar baseline activity and distributed surface state for the same circuit and stimulus.\nagent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:20:Define a first-class surface-wave model contract in library code and document the numerical and scientific choices behind it. Centralize wave-model naming, parameter normalization and serialization, contract-version metadata, and design-note discovery so later planning, execution, and result tooling can resolve one canonical `surface_wave` family without hardcoded strings. The design note should compare the candidate model families named in the roadmap, choose the default family for Milestone 10, define the state variables, propagation term, damping term, recovery or refractory behavior, synaptic source injection semantics, nonlinearities, optional anisotropy and branching extensions, and state what counts as physically meaningful behavior versus a numerical artifact.\nagent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:69:Milestone 10 cannot begin with multi-neuron wiring if the repo still lacks the actual single-neuron wave solver. The current simulator framework has no morphology-resolved state container, no canonical sparse operator application path for surface or patch state, no stability-aware time integrator for the chosen model family, and no deterministic stepping semantics for a distributed field state. Without that core, later tickets will either duplicate low-level solver logic or couple together incomplete one-off kernels that are too opaque to trust scientifically.\nagent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:92:- Area: model dynamics / anisotropy / morphology-aware mechanics\nagent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:95:A purely linear propagation kernel is not enough to satisfy the roadmap's required model ingredients. Milestone 10 explicitly calls for recovery or refractory behavior, nonlinearities, optional anisotropy, and optional branching effects, yet the repo currently has no disciplined way to represent any of those in a scientifically reviewable form. If they are added ad hoc inside the step loop, the team will not be able to tell whether a changed output came from the intended model family, a hidden numerical trick, or a morphology-specific tuning loophole.\nagent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:118:- Area: coupling execution / source injection / circuit dynamics\nagent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:121:Milestone 10 is not complete when a single neuron can support a wave in isolation. The roadmap requires multi-neuron propagation, which means the engine must consume the Milestone 7 coupling bundle, sample presynaptic wave readouts, apply delays and signs deterministically, and inject the resulting source terms onto the postsynaptic state space. Right now there is no wave-side coupling executor, no canonical definition of how a presynaptic surface state becomes a postsynaptic source, and no deterministic update ordering for a coupled morphology-resolved circuit.\nagent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:127:- A canonical API can construct and execute a coupled multi-neuron `surface_wave` circuit from selected roots, operator bundles, and Milestone 7 coupling assets using only local repo artifacts.\nagent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:129:- The same resolved circuit, coupling assets, and seed produce the same realized injection schedule and multi-neuron state evolution deterministically.\nagent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:131:- Regression coverage validates deterministic multi-neuron propagation on a small fixture circuit, including at least one coupling-sensitive or delay-sensitive case.\nagent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:135:- A focused integration-style test that runs a small coupled fixture circuit and asserts deterministic inter-neuron source injection plus multi-neuron propagation behavior\nagent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:147:The milestone's done-when clause explicitly says the engine must run under actual visual input, but the repo still has no public path that executes `surface_wave` runs end to end from the experiment manifest. Without a manifest-driven execution path, the wave solver will remain an internal kernel that cannot be compared fairly against baseline mode, cannot feed the UI, and cannot prove that the same circuit and same input stream are reaching both simulator modes through a shared workflow.\nagent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:154:- The written bundle follows the shared simulator result contract while adding the wave-specific metadata, state summaries, or snapshot references needed to interpret morphology-resolved runs.\nagent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:173:Milestone 10 is only complete if parameters can be swept systematically and if the team can inspect whether the realized wave behavior is physically meaningful rather than numerically suspicious. Right now the repo has no standard local workflow for sweeping the new model parameters, no deterministic stability or artifact diagnostics, and no offline inspection report that shows how single-neuron and coupled wave trajectories behave over time. Without that tooling, the team will be forced to judge the engine from raw arrays or one-off notebooks, which is too weak a foundation for Milestones 12 and 13.\nagent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:182:- The implementation surfaces clear pass, warn, or fail conditions for obviously unstable, degenerate, or numerically suspicious runs rather than leaving every interpretation to manual inspection.\nagent_tickets/milestone_10_surface_wave_engine_tickets.md:202:Perform a senior-level verification pass over the completed Milestone 10 implementation and publish a concise readiness report in-repo. This pass should exercise the full local `surface_wave` workflow on fixture assets and at least one representative manifest path, confirm that documentation matches shipped behavior, verify that outputs remain comparison-ready for baseline mode, identify any numerical or scientific risks that remain open, and either fix those gaps directly or record them as explicit follow-on issues. Treat this as an integration and audit ticket rather than a net-new feature ticket.\ntests/test_simulator_runtime.py:132:                (\"circuit_dynamic_state\", \"circuit_output\", \"mean\", \"activation_au\"),\ntests/test_simulator_runtime.py:153:    def test_run_to_completion_is_deterministic_for_fixture_circuit(self) -> None:\ntests/test_simulator_runtime.py:210:                    scope=\"circuit_output\",\ntests/test_s