mat_version\": \"json_mixed_morphology_state_bundle.v1\",\ntests/test_simulator_result_contract.py:565:                            \"morphology_class\": \"surface_neuron\",\ntests/test_simulator_result_contract.py:569:                            \"morphology_class\": \"skeleton_neuron\",\ntests/test_simulator_result_contract.py:573:                            \"morphology_class\": \"point_neuron\",\ntests/test_simulator_result_contract.py:588:                bundle_paths.extension_root_directory / \"mixed_morphology_state_bundle.json\",\ntests/test_simulator_result_contract.py:592:            discovered_roots = discover_simulator_root_morphology_metadata(loaded_metadata)\ntests/test_simulator_result_contract.py:601:                [item[\"morphology_class\"] for item in discovered_roots],\ntests/test_simulator_result_contract.py:612:            self.assertEqual(point_state_payload[\"morphology_class\"], \"point_neuron\")\nscripts/23_numerical_validation.py:7:from flywire_wave.validation_numerics import execute_numerical_validation_workflow\nscripts/23_numerical_validation.py:13:            \"Run the Milestone 13 numerical-sanity validation suite on local \"\nscripts/23_numerical_validation.py:44:    summary = execute_numerical_validation_workflow(\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:3:Compiled project notes for planning, scientific framing, circuit definition, input design, BCI relevance, optimization, and presentation.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:18:- [Milestone 2 Circuit Boundary](#milestone-2-circuit-boundary)\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:31:The core question behind this project is whether neural computation might depend on more than just point-to-point firing. Our hypothesis is that signals traveling across the physical structure of neurons — what we model as surface-wave dynamics on neuronal morphology — can meaningfully shape how a circuit processes information.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:33:To test that, we did not just build a solver. We built the full experimental scaffold around it. We locked the scientific claim, defined a biologically defensible fruit fly visual subcircuit, created reproducible data registries and subset selection tools, converted neuron morphology into wave-ready geometry and operators, built the baseline simulator for fair comparison, and then integrated the first working surface-wave simulation path on top of that.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:35:What makes this valid is that the system is structured as an actual falsifiable experiment. The same circuit and same stimulus can be run through both a conventional baseline model and our surface-wave model, with shared readouts and milestone-specific readiness checks. So even though we did not finish the full end-to-end scientific proof, we *did* build the framework needed to test the idea rigorously.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:54:Build a connectome-constrained fruit fly visual simulation where selected neurons carry surface-wave dynamics across their morphology, driven by a synthetic visual scene generator, and presented through a strong interactive UI / analysis layer.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:60:Math/physics-heavy = model formulation, numerical operators, stability, wave equations, discretization choices, validation metrics, analysis design\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:110:choose the circuit\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:126:Morphology-resolved surface dynamics constitute an additional intraneuronal computational degree of freedom, capable of shaping circuit input-output transformations through distributed spatiotemporal state on neuronal structure.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:129:In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:134:surface-localized inputs on explicit T4/T5 morphology regions\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:135:surface propagation over a morphology graph\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:147:P0: canonical point baseline using passive leaky linear non-spiking single-compartment neurons matched to the same circuit and readout\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:152: In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:154: It should add distributed, morphology-bound intraneuronal state and nothing else that can trivially explain the result.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:158: The same stimulus driving the same circuit in two models, producing a small but real output difference that shrinks or disappears when geometry is shuffled.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:169:Strong: the shared-readout change shrinks or disappears when morphology or synapse topology is shuffled\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:174:10–25 s: split screen with matched point baseline on the left and surface model on the right for the same T4/T5-centered circuit\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:181:split view showing baseline scalar activity versus surface-state activity on morphology\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:182:shared output trace overlay for the same circuit and stimulus\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:211:task-level differences\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:234:#### Milestone 2 — Lock the circuit boundary\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:239:Choose and freeze the smallest scientifically defensible circuit boundary for the first real simulation pass.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:241:##### Locked circuit decision\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:272:LPi/LPTC inventory or wide-field tangential-cell circuitry\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:283:Promote additional circuitry only when it becomes the leading limitation:\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:306:both of you can explain why this boundary is sufficient for the first morphology-sensitive test\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:383:#### Milestone 5 — Build the geometry ingestion and multiresolution morphology pipeline\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:423:Turn neuron surfaces into simulation-ready numerical objects.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:451:propagation on the surface is numerically stable\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:584:The wave model is far more convincing if the exact same circuit can be run in:\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:644:specifying what behaviors are physically meaningful vs numerical artifacts\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:652:#### Milestone 11 — Add hybrid morphology classes\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:680:#### Milestone 12 — Define readouts and task layer\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:713:at least one task metric is automated\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:716:#### Milestone 13 — Build the validation ladder\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:745:stable task outputs\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:822:shuffled morphology\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:882:Show where the active visual circuit sits inside the larger female brain context.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:961:one end-to-end input frame reaches the chosen circuit\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1010:one “wow” morphology activity visualization\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1054:task readouts\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1080:designing the validation ladder\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1100:Milestone 13\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1110:a Grant vs Jack task board\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1119:I’d also make the default target **the visual motion pathway**, not the whole brain and not olfaction. There is already a strong precedent for this: the 2024 connectome-constrained fly visual model used 64 cell types arranged over a 721-column hexagonal lattice, spanning 45,669 neurons, and was trained on optic-flow estimation from video sequences sampled onto that lattice. The official `flyvis` implementation explicitly supports pretrained models and custom stimuli, which makes it a great reference architecture for your input/task side even if your wave dynamics are completely different. ([nature.com](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-024-07939-3))\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1128:“Wave-like propagation on neuron surfaces changes or enriches the functional behavior of a connectome-constrained fly visual circuit.”\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1131:“A user can place the fly in a synthetic visual scene, watch input flow into a selected visual circuit, and compare classical point-like dynamics versus surface-wave dynamics in real time.”\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1135:- you define the task outputs you care about,\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1148:### Milestone 2 — Lock the circuit boundary\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1212:### Milestone 5 — Geometry ingestion and multiresolution morphology pipeline\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1261:- you can quantify numerical stability and energy behavior,\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1322:- the exact same circuit can run on simple lab stimuli and on generated scenes,\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1378:### Milestone 11 — Hybrid morphology strategy\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1394:### Milestone 12 — Readouts and task layer\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1411:Existing connectome-constrained visual work used optic-flow estimation as the training/evaluation task, so using optic-flow or motion readout as one of your benchmark tasks is very well aligned with prior visual-system modeling. ([nature.com](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-024-07939-3))\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1416:- at least one task metric is quantitative and automated.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1418:### Milestone 13 — Validation ladder\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1420:Validation should move from “physics sanity” to “circuit sanity” to “task sanity.”\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1459:3. **3D morphology pane**  \nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1468:This is exactly the kind of integrated structure/function workflow that fruit-fly platforms like FlyBrainLab were built around: 3D exploration, creation of executable circuits, and interactive exploration of circuit logic. ([github.com](https://github.com/FlyBrainLab/FlyBrainLab))\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1497:- shuffled morphology\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1533:Once the visual-circuit simulator is alive, expand the role of the rest of the female brain from “unused metadata” to “context layer.”\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1560:12. add task/readout layer  \nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1575:- one quantitative task metric\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1586:> **Morphology-resolved surface dynamics constitute an additional intraneuronal computational degree of freedom, capable of shaping circuit input-output transformations through distributed spatiotemporal state on neuronal structure.**\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1590:> **In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.**\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1606:> **It should endow selected neurons with explicit distributed state over morphology, so that synapse landing position, geodesic separation, and local spatiotemporal propagation can influence integration before the signal is collapsed to a downstream readout.**\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1617:- **Surface propagation.** State evolves over the morphology by local propagation on the surface graph or skeleton-derived patch graph.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1619:- **Shared output readout.** Downstream circuitry still sees an ordinary scalar or low-dimensional readout, so comparison with the baseline is fair.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1663:> **The wave model should add distributed morphology-bound state, and nothing else that can trivially explain the effect.**\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1679:Meaning: a measurable difference between wave and baseline on a readout both models share, where that difference depends on intact morphology or synapse topology and is challengeable by stronger reduced baselines.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1689:That is more aligned with your revised goal than raw “task accuracy.” It asks whether the surface layer changes the transformation itself, not whether it produces a huge gain.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1721:That shared-readout change shrinks or disappears when morphology or synapse topology is shuffled.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1762:> **The same circuit, under the same stimulus, produces a small but real output difference when morphology-bound surface dynamics are present, and that difference depends on intact geometry.**\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1772:right = surface model on the same T4/T5-centered circuit\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1817:> **“The wave layer changes the computation at all, and the change is tied to morphology.”**\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1826:2. **Geometry dependence** through topology/morphology perturbation\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1839:It should add **distributed, morphology-bound intraneuronal state** and nothing else that can trivially explain the result.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1845:The **same stimulus** driving the **same circuit** in two models, producing a **small but real output difference** that **shrinks or disappears when geometry is shuffled**.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1855:Lock Milestone 2 to a **central-equatorial local motion patch built around one horizontal ON/OFF channel**, not to a generic lamina-to-behavior slab. The default active graph should **surface-simulate only T4a and T5a**, over just the columns subtending the chosen stimulus aperture plus a one-ring halo, because T4/T5 are the first direction-selective neurons, their subtype geometry is best behaved near the center of the eye, and T4 dendrites sample a local seven-column unit hexagon rather than an arbitrary wide field. Their **direct feedforward partners** should be active only in reduced form: Mi1, Tm3, Mi4 and Mi9 on the ON side, and Tm1, Tm2, Tm4 and Tm9 on the OFF side. Photoreceptors and lamina should stay **abstracted** as retinotopically aligned drive, because the first claim is not about phototransduction or lamina morphology, and the known direct T4/T5 inputs are already sufficient to impose the relevant spatial-temporal drive pattern on the motion detectors. Readout should stop at **T4a/T5a axon terminals** in lobula plate layer 1, not extend yet into LPi or tangential-cell circuitry. LPi neurons, HS/VS/LPTCs, and the rest of the brain should remain context-only, because downstream motion opponency and optic-flow tuning operate at much larger pooling scales and would force a much broader field before you have shown the core intraneuronal effect. This boundary is intentionally much smaller than recent connectome-constrained whole-visual-field models, because Milestone 2 is about falsifying a small geometry-sensitive effect, not maximizing anatomical coverage. The truly minimal T4-only ON circuit is scientifically defensible, but I would **not** lock it as the default, because adding the matched T5 OFF sister channel costs little and sharply reduces the risk that any effect is an ON-pathway artifact. Conversely, adding LPi/LPTC circuitry now would blur whether the first effect comes from intraneuronal morphology or from downstream opponency. So the decision-ready default is: **central patch, T4a/T5a in surface mode, direct ON/OFF columnar inputs in reduced mode, terminal readout only, everything else context or excluded**. ([pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7069908/))\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1859:- Put morphology-resolved dynamics only where morphology is mechanistically implicated **and** strong simple baselines already pose a real challenge: that means T4/T5, not lamina, not whole-brain feedback. ([nature.com](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-017-0046-4))\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1861:- Prefer **local feedforward motion circuitry** over wide-field/global motion circuitry; once a neuron pools over hundreds of T4/T5 cells, it belongs to a later milestone. ([nature.com](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-023-01443-z))\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1868:*Here, “active” means numerically simulated at either surface or reduced fidelity.*\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1872:- **Selected T4a cells in one central-equatorial contiguous patch (surface-simulated).** Role: first ON direction-selective local motion detectors. Surface-wave relevance: maximal, because direction selectivity emerges in T4/T5 and the hypothesis lives or dies at this computation. Needed for the first falsifiable test: **yes**. What is lost if omitted: the project is no longer testing morphology in the first known motion-detector stage. Can it be abstracted: **no**. ([pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7069908/))\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1898:- **Object/looming-specialized branches of the visual system.** These are legitimate visual circuits, but they test a different computational question from local motion detection and would dilute the Milestone 2 hypothesis. ([nature.com](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-024-07981-1))\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1943:- **Main scientific risk:** downstream pooling and LPi circuitry can dominate the phenotype, making it harder to attribute the first effect to intraneuronal morphology.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1952:It is the smallest boundary I would actually sign off on for Milestone 2. The minimal T4a-only circuit is enough to debug the wave engine, but it leaves you too exposed to the criticism that any geometry-sensitive effect is peculiar to one polarity channel. The balanced choice adds only the matched OFF sister pathway, keeps the active field local, keeps the readout at T4/T5 rather than in wide-field tangential circuitry, and gives you a built-in replication across contrast polarity without importing LPi/LPTC-scale complications. It also respects the strongest baseline challenge: simple single-compartment and connectome-constrained models already do a lot in this system, so the first win has to come from a clean local morphology test, not from extra downstream machinery. Concretely, I would lock the first vertical slice to **T4a/T5a + direct ON/OFF reduced inputs + central patch + terminal readout**, driven by bright and dark moving edges or apparent-motion bar pairs along the chosen horizontal axis, with **geometry-sensitive null-direction suppression** as the primary metric and **response latency** as the mechanistic companion. ([nature.com](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-017-0046-4))\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1956:- **Trap: simulating full photoreceptor and lamina dynamics.** Avoid it. R1–R6 and L1/L2/L3 establish the motion channels, but explicit lamina biophysics will mostly add upstream detail rather than sharpen a T4/T5 morphology claim. Promote them only if reviewers can plausibly say your input abstraction hid the critical delays. ([pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4243710/))\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1960:- **Trap: adding LPi and HS/VS because they feel like a “real output.”** Avoid it for Milestone 2. LPi/LPTC circuitry is where global motion opponency and flow-field selectivity emerge, but that machinery pools over much larger spatial scales and will force field-of-view expansion before you know whether the surface state matters at all. Promote it only after a clear T4/T5-level effect. ([nature.com](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-023-01443-z))\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2018:- **Distributed redundancy in the direct inputs means “no effect” is hard to interpret.** Mi1/Tm3 are major ON inputs, but Mi4/Mi9 and parallel circuitry make the pathway robust; similarly, T5 input contributions are distributed and Tm9 is unusually important. A null result could mean “wave effects are absent,” but it could also mean “this stimulus and this reduced boundary let the classical circuit absorb the computation.” ([pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6845231/))\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2024:- **What would force a boundary revision later:** a persistent upstream-delay confound would justify promoting lamina point models; a systematic OFF-pathway failure would justify CT1 promotion; a first clean T4/T5 effect that vanishes downstream would justify the LPi/HS extension; and a claim about optic flow or behavior would justify a larger patch and broader lobula plate circuitry. ([pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4243710/))\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2093:For Milestones 11, 12, and 13, your own roadmap already frames them as **hybrid morphology classes**, **readouts/task layer**, and **validation ladder**, and the repo’s readiness pass already points at the downstream workstreams as **mixed_fidelity**, **metrics**, and **validation**. So the fastest path is to build directly on the current solver/execution stack, not start a new architecture.  \nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2200:#### Patch 3: add a numerical tripwire\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2225:This is Milestone 13 work that pays for itself instantly.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2267:#### Milestone 13: validation\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2274:That is the minimum serious validation ladder.\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2457:3. **Add numerical tripwire**\nagent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2460:6. **Implement Milestone 13 validators**\nsrc/flywire_wave/surface_wave_inspection.py:813:        circuit_assets=_require_mapping(\nsrc/flywire_wave/surface_wave_inspection.py:814:            arm_plan.get(\"circuit_assets\"),\nsrc/flywire_wave/surface_wave_inspection.py:815:            field_name=\"arm_plan.circuit_assets\",\nsrc/flywire_wave/surface_wave_inspection.py:861:    circuit = resolved.build_circuit()\nsrc/flywire_wave/surface_wave_inspection.py:862:    circuit.initialize_zero()\nsrc/flywire_wave/surface_wave_inspection.py:877:        circuit.step_shared(surface_drives_by_root=surface_drives_by_root)\nsrc/flywire_wave/surface_wave_inspection.py:878:    wave_run = circuit.finalize()\nsrc/flywire_wave/surface_wave_inspection.py:1190:            description=\"Driven coupled runs should retain some morphology-resolved spatial contrast.\",\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-002_rationale.md:1:# FW-M13-002 Rationale\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-002_rationale.md:5:Milestone 13 needed one library-owned planning surface above the existing\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-002_rationale.md:16:The implementation in `flywire_wave.validation_planning` closes that gap.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-002_rationale.md:36:- Perturbation suites are represented even though later Milestone 13 tickets\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-002_rationale.md:48:- `tests/test_validation_planning.py` resolves a representative fixture manifest\nscripts/22_milestone12_readiness.py:24:        description=\"Run the Milestone 12 task-layer integration verification pass and publish a readiness report.\"\nagent_tickets/milestone_9_baseline_non_wave_simulator_tickets.md:50:- The plan records the manifest-level stimulus or retinal input reference, selected circuit or subset identity, coupling sources, timing, seed handling, baseline-family parameters, and deterministic output locations needed to launch a run.\nagent_tickets/milestone_9_baseline_non_wave_simulator_tickets.md:72:Build the core simulator execution framework in library code. The framework should own run initialization, fixed-timestep stepping, state storage, deterministic update ordering, lightweight instrumentation hooks, and structured snapshot extraction. Design it so scalar baseline state is easy to implement now, while the same top-level run interface can later host morphology-resolved state for `surface_wave` without rewriting orchestration, serialization, or monitoring logic.\nagent_tickets/milestone_9_baseline_non_wave_simulator_tickets.md:79:- Regression coverage validates deterministic stepping on local fixture circuits, stable initialization and finalization behavior, and representative snapshot extraction.\nagent_tickets/milestone_9_baseline_non_wave_simulator_tickets.md:83:- A focused simulator-runtime test that steps a small fixture circuit and asserts deterministic state evolution plus lifecycle behavior\nagent_tickets/milestone_9_baseline_non_wave_simulator_tickets.md:118:- Area: input integration / connectivity / circuit execution\nagent_tickets/milestone_9_baseline_non_wave_simulator_tickets.md:121:Even with a stepping engine and neuron models, Milestone 9 is still incomplete unless the baseline simulator can run the actual connectome-constrained circuit with the repo’s canonical inputs. Right now there is no baseline-side integration path that consumes the selected-root roster, local coupling bundles, topology condition, and canonical time-varying input stream and turns them into recurrent per-neuron updates. Without that integration, the baseline mode is only a toy dynamical system rather than the matched circuit control the roadmap calls for.\nagent_tickets/milestone_9_baseline_non_wave_simulator_tickets.md:124:Implement the input and connectivity integration layer that drives the baseline simulator from the repo’s canonical assets. The implementation should resolve the selected circuit, ingest the relevant Milestone 7 coupling bundles, apply the intact or shuffled topology condition from the manifest plan, and feed the simulator with the canonical time-varying input stream expected by the visual-input stack. Keep the integration deterministic, cache-friendly, and asset-contract-aware so the same circuit and same input can later be run through `baseline` and `surface_wave` modes without changing the data handoff surface.\nagent_tickets/milestone_9_baseline_non_wave_simulator_tickets.md:127:- A canonical API can construct one executable baseline circuit run from selected roots, coupling bundles, topology condition, and a canonical input stream using only local repo artifacts.\nagent_tickets/milestone_9_baseline_non_wave_simulator_tickets.md:129:- The same resolved circuit and input asset identity always produce the same baseline wiring and drive schedule for a given seed and config.\nagent_tickets/milestone_9_baseline_non_wave_simulator_tickets.md:131:- Regression coverage validates deterministic circuit execution on small fixture circuits, including at least one intact-versus-shuffled or delay-sensitive case.\nagent_tickets/milestone_9_baseline_non_wave_simulator_tickets.md:135:- A focused integration-style test that runs a small fixture circuit with canonical input and coupling assets and asserts deterministic recurrent state updates\nagent_tickets/milestone_9_baseline_non_wave_simulator_tickets.md:138:Assume the earlier Milestone 9 tickets are already in place and that the relevant local input contracts from upstream milestones exist or have fixture stand-ins. The key deliverable is a matched-circuit control path, not a one-off current injection demo. Before finishing this ticket, stage all changes made for it and create a non-amended commit that includes those changes.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-007_rationale.md:1:# FW-M13-007 Rationale\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-007_rationale.md:5:Milestone 13 already had four executable validation layers, but it still lacked\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-007_rationale.md:36:  It uses deterministic local synthetic cases for numerical, morphology,\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-007_rationale.md:37:  circuit, and task layers so CI can run a meaningful regression check without\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-007_rationale.md:51:  layer is validated alongside the existing Milestone 13 suites.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-007_rationale.md:76:  Milestone 13 and Milestone 14 code can consume one shared review surface\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:17:Milestone 5 produces geometry bundles that are useful preprocessing artifacts, but they are not yet a stable numerical-operator contract. The repo has no canonical definition for which operator family is being used, which auxiliary matrices and geometry fields must be serialized, how boundary handling is represented, or how downstream code should discover coarse-versus-fine transfer structures. Without a versioned contract and an explicit design note, later simulator work will bind itself to ad hoc archive keys and undocumented mathematical assumptions.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:20:Define a first-class operator bundle contract for Milestone 6 and document the numerical design choices behind it. The implementation should centralize artifact naming and metadata in library code, extend the processed manifest so downstream consumers can discover operator assets without hardcoded filenames, and add a markdown design note that compares the viable discretization families before committing to the default. The design note should be decisive: pick the default fine-surface discretization, explain when fallback behavior is allowed, state which quantities should be conserved or damped, and record the stability-relevant assumptions the later wave engine will inherit.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:43:The current processed surface graph is still a Milestone 5 scaffold. It exposes simplified mesh connectivity and a uniform graph Laplacian, but it does not yet provide the numerical objects Milestone 6 actually needs: geodesic neighborhoods, boundary masks, local tangent frames, metric-aware weights, or a surface operator whose supporting geometry is explicit enough to debug and validate. That leaves the repo unable to build a simulation-ready single-neuron surface state without rewriting the existing graph archive by hand.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:46:Implement the fine-surface operator builder that turns a simplified mesh bundle into a numerically meaningful fine-resolution operator artifact. Use the discretization family chosen in `FW-M6-001`, and serialize the supporting geometry needed to inspect or reuse the operator later: adjacency and edge geometry, local areas or mass terms, normals and tangent frames, geodesic-neighborhood structures, and boundary masks. Keep sparse assembly in library code, make the script layer an orchestrator only, and ensure the output is deterministic for the same mesh and config.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:103:- Identity anisotropy reproduces the isotropic operator exactly or within a documented numerical tolerance enforced by tests.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:121:Milestone 6 is only complete if the team can initialize a pulse on one neuron, verify that surface propagation behaves stably enough for later engine work, compare coarse and fine operators quantitatively, and inspect the results without digging through raw arrays. Right now there is no standard harness that exercises those numerical behaviors, no operator quality report, and no offline visualization flow for reviewing what the assembled operators are actually doing on the mesh.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:147:Even if the Milestone 6 build tickets land individually, the repo still needs one explicit follow-up pass that verifies the pieces work together as a coherent operator pipeline. Without a dedicated implementation-verification ticket, it is too easy to stop at local success on isolated subtasks while leaving behind contract drift, missing docs, broken report paths, weak regression coverage, or untested assumptions between fine operators, coarse operators, transfer maps, and QA tooling.\nagent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:178:pipeline on real morphology, yet it does not exercise the exact\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_follow_on_tickets.md:17:The Milestone 11 readiness pass now proves that one surface root, one skeleton root, one routed point root, and one isolated point-surrogate root can coexist through planning, execution, cross-class routing, serialization, visualization, and surrogate inspection. That is the right first integration gate, but the shipped fixture is still intentionally small and synthetic: the skeleton asset is branch-free, the policy and inspection ladder exercise only one promotion candidate, and the mixed routes cover one representative loop rather than a broader delayed or branched circuit family.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_follow_on_tickets.md:49:The shipped mixed-fidelity inspection workflow now proves that a manifest-only fidelity promotion can produce a valid higher-fidelity reference arm for an isolated surrogate root. That keeps the local readiness gate deterministic and coherent, but it also exposes a remaining limitation: if the promoted root already participates in mixed-class coupling edges, the workflow still rewrites the manifest without regenerating incident coupling anchor geometry for the new morphology class.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_follow_on_tickets.md:52:Extend the mixed-fidelity inspection workflow so it can build coupling-compatible reference variants for promoted roots that have incoming or outgoing mixed-class coupling bundles. The result should let a reviewer compare a surrogate root against a higher-fidelity reference without first hand-editing the readiness fixture to isolate that root from the routed circuit.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-001_rationale.md:1:# FW-M13-001 Rationale\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-001_rationale.md:6:Milestone 13 vocabulary across scripts or docs. The module owns:\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-001_rationale.md:24:threshold contents. That keeps the Milestone 13 vocabulary stable without\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-001_rationale.md:46:Milestone 13 work can rely on one canonical vocabulary.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-001_rationale.md:53:than missing numerical kernels.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:10:## FW-M11-001 - Freeze a versioned hybrid-morphology contract, fidelity taxonomy, and approximation design note\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:17:The repo now has strong contracts for geometry bundles, coupling bundles, retinal input, baseline execution, and `surface_wave` execution, but there is still no first-class contract for mixed morphology fidelity inside one simulator run. Role labels such as `surface_simulated`, `skeleton_simulated`, and `point_simulated` already exist in registry and coupling code, yet they do not currently define one canonical simulator-facing meaning for required assets, state layout, coupling anchor resolution, readout semantics, approximation limits, or promotion and demotion rules. Without a versioned hybrid contract, Milestone 11 work will drift across planner code, runtime glue, and result serialization, and it will be too easy to implement a mixed run that is operationally convenient but scientifically ambiguous.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:20:Define a library-owned hybrid-morphology contract and publish a concise design note that locks the Milestone 11 vocabulary. The contract should name the supported simulator-facing morphology classes, their required and optional local assets, their state and readout semantics, the allowed cross-class coupling routes, and the invariants that must remain stable when a neuron is promoted from point to skeleton to surface fidelity. Prefer extending the existing `surface_wave` planning and execution path with per-root morphology-class metadata instead of introducing a separate top-level simulator mode, unless a hard compatibility blocker is discovered and documented.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:23:- There is one canonical hybrid-morphology contract in library code with explicit identifiers for `surface_neuron`, `skeleton_neuron`, and `point_neuron` or equivalently named normalized classes.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:26:- `docs/pipeline_notes.md` is updated so mixed morphology sits alongside the existing geometry, coupling, retinal, and simulator contracts rather than living only in code comments.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:31:- A focused unit test that builds fixture hybrid-morphology metadata and asserts deterministic contract serialization plus class discovery\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:43:The current simulation planner can resolve baseline and `surface_wave` arms, but it still assumes one morphology-state strategy per arm. In particular, the wave-side planning path hardcodes one surface-oriented state resolution, one coupling anchor resolution, and one operator inventory story for every selected root. That prevents a single run from cleanly mixing full surface neurons with skeleton approximations and point placeholders, and it leaves no canonical place to express class overrides from registry defaults, manifest arms, or future scheduler-driven promotion rules.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:46:Extend the library-owned planning layer so a manifest plus config resolves into a deterministic mixed-fidelity execution plan with explicit per-root fidelity assignment. Normalize the chosen morphology class for each selected root, validate the required local assets for that class, record the realized approximation route, and preserve stable arm ordering and result-bundle identity. The planner should support registry-default roles, arm-level overrides, and a narrow policy surface for future promotion and demotion logic without forcing every caller to invent its own class-resolution code.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:49:- There is one canonical API that resolves a manifest plus local config into normalized per-root morphology assignments for a mixed run.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:50:- The normalized arm plan records, for each selected root, the realized morphology class, required local asset references, state and coupling resolution, and any approximation-policy provenance needed to explain why that class was chosen.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:62:## FW-M11-003 - Refactor the wave runtime around a pluggable morphology-class interface while preserving current surface behavior\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:69:The current `surface_wave` runtime is organized around a surface-only execution path with `SingleNeuronSurfaceWaveSolver`, surface operator bundles, and patch-cloud coupling semantics baked directly into the circuit assembly. That is a good Milestone 10 implementation, but it is not yet a stable architecture for Milestone 11 because adding a skeleton or point class would currently require threading special cases through the same surface-specific code paths. Without a shared morphology-class runtime interface, every later fidelity class will either duplicate simulator plumbing or force a risky rewrite after functionality already lands.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:72:Refactor the mixed-fidelity runtime around a narrow pluggable morphology-class interface and migrate the existing surface implementation onto it first. The interface should cover initialization, stepping, state export, readout export, source injection, and coupling-facing projection in a way that remains deterministic and inspectable. Preserve current surface-run behavior and result compatibility while making it possible for later tickets to add skeleton and point implementations without changing the surrounding simulator architecture again.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:75:- There is a library-owned morphology-class runtime interface or adapter layer that the simulator uses instead of calling the surface solver directly as a special case.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:95:The repo already fetches raw SWC skeletons and uses skeleton anchors for coupling fallback, but it still has no simulator-facing skeleton morphology class. There is no canonical processed skeleton-graph handoff for runtime consumption, no deterministic skeleton-state container, and no graph-based approximation path that can stand in for a surface neuron while still participating in the same simulator architecture. Without that, Milestone 11 would claim skeleton support while actually treating skeletons only as coupling-localization helpers.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:98:Implement the first real skeleton-neuron approximation path end to end. Add a deterministic skeleton asset handoff suitable for runtime use, define the graph operator or reduced propagation structure required by the chosen approximation strategy, and implement a skeleton runtime adapter that conforms to the shared morphology-class interface from `FW-M11-003`. The resulting class should support initialization, stepping, source injection, readout export, and coupling projection using only local cached artifacts and documented approximation semantics.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:105:- Regression coverage validates deterministic skeleton-asset discovery, stable single-neuron skeleton stepping on local fixtures, and compatibility with the shared morphology-class runtime interface.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:124:Implement the point-neuron morphology class inside the shared mixed-fidelity runtime and add fidelity-agnostic state and readout serialization for mixed runs. Reuse existing baseline family behavior where that is scientifically appropriate, but normalize it through the Milestone 11 contract so a point placeholder can coexist with surface and skeleton neurons in one result bundle. The written outputs should let later metrics, validation, and UI code discover per-root class, state summary, and readout payloads without reverse-engineering runtime internals.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:127:- A mixed-fidelity plan can include one or more point-neuron placeholders that execute through the shared morphology-class runtime rather than a separate baseline-only path.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:128:- Result-bundle metadata records the realized morphology class for every root and points to class-appropriate but contract-consistent state and readout artifacts.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:147:Milestone 7 defined a fallback-aware coupling contract, but the live simulator still lacks execution-time routing between mixed morphology classes. Today the wave runtime assumes surface patch clouds on both sides of a coupling component, while a real Milestone 11 run must support combinations such as surface-to-skeleton, skeleton-to-surface, skeleton-to-point, and point-to-surface without changing the scientific sign, delay, and aggregation semantics. Without a canonical router, mixed-fidelity execution will either ignore class mismatches or quietly mutate coupling meaning across code paths.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:150:Build the library-owned coupling router that converts normalized coupling assets into executable source-projection and target-injection operations across all supported morphology-class pairs. Preserve the Milestone 7 sign, delay, aggregation, and fallback hierarchy semantics while making the class-to-class translation explicit and testable. The router should explain which representation pair was realized for each executed component and fail clearly when a requested cross-class route is unsupported or scientifically disallowed.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:153:- A canonical runtime layer can execute coupling between the supported morphology-class pairs using the normalized hybrid plan and existing coupling assets.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:190:Assume `FW-M11-001` through `FW-M11-006` are already in place. This is not the final validation ladder from Milestone 13; it is the first approximation-audit layer that keeps Milestone 11 honest and gives Grant a structured place to review surrogate quality. Do not attempt to create a git commit as part of this ticket.\nagent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md:213:- `python3 scripts/run_agent_tickets.py --tickets-file agent_tickets/milestone_11_hybrid_morphology_classes_tickets.md --ticket-id FW-M11-008 --dry-run --runner true`\nagent_tickets/milestone_5_geometry_pipeline_tickets.md:10:## FW-M5-001 - Define a versioned geometry asset contract for multiresolution morphology bundles\nagent_tickets/milestone_5_geometry_pipeline_tickets.md:20:Introduce a single versioned geometry asset contract in library code and apply it across the fetch and build steps. Define the canonical per-neuron output layout, manifest fields, naming rules, and build metadata needed for multiresolution morphology assets. The contract should make it obvious which raw and processed files belong to a neuron, which config values shaped them, and which bundle version downstream code is reading.\nagent_tickets/milestone_5_geometry_pipeline_tickets.md:62:## FW-M5-003 - Build explicit surface-graph and patch-graph artifacts for the multiresolution morphology bundle\nagent_tickets/milestone_5_geometry_pipeline_tickets.md:69:`scripts/03_build_wave_assets.py` currently emits a simplified mesh and one combined graph archive with an example patch mask. That is a good scaffold, but it is not yet a true multiresolution morphology bundle. Milestone 5 calls for explicit surface and patch graph assets, stable mappings between resolutions, and a clearer representation boundary between fine surface data and coarse simulation-ready patches.\nagent_tickets/milestone_5_geometry_pipeline_tickets.md:95:The repo currently has no quantitative answer to a basic Milestone 5 question: did simplification and patchification preserve the geometry features that matter for later wave propagation experiments? Without descriptor sidecars and QA thresholds, the pipeline can produce smaller assets but cannot tell us whether they are still faithful enough for downstream numerical work.\nagent_tickets/milestone_5_geometry_pipeline_tickets.md:98:Add a descriptor and QA stage that computes wave-relevant geometry summaries for raw, simplified, and coarse representations, then compares them against configurable error budgets. Capture both the implemented metrics and the reasoning behind them in a short markdown design note so later milestones have a documented baseline for what counts as an acceptable morphology approximation.\nagent_tickets/repo_review_tickets.md:17:The pipeline currently interprets relative paths from YAML against the caller's current working directory instead of the config file location or the repository root. That makes the commands brittle in automation, editor tasks, and any shell session that is not already sitting at the repo root.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-003_rationale.md:1:# FW-M13-003 Rationale\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-003_rationale.md:5:Milestone 13 needed a first executable numerical-sanity layer, not just the\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-003_rationale.md:6:taxonomy and planning vocabulary added in FW-M13-001 and FW-M13-002. The new\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-003_rationale.md:15:- writes deterministic validation artifacts in the Milestone 13 bundle layout\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-003_rationale.md:23:- The workflow resolves a numerical-only validation plan.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-003_rationale.md:24:  The repo-wide validation ladder already reserves bundle paths and validator\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-003_rationale.md:26:  This ticket therefore resolves the numerical subset directly from the same\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-003_rationale.md:27:  normalized `validation` config surface so local numerical execution remains\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-003_rationale.md:48:make numerical-validate CONFIG=path/to/config.yaml MANIFEST=path/to/manifest.yaml\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-003_rationale.md:51:That target runs `scripts/23_numerical_validation.py`, resolves the numerical\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-003_rationale.md:60:under the deterministic Milestone 13 validation bundle directory.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-003_rationale.md:79:- The first workflow executes only the numerical layer.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-003_rationale.md:80:  Morphology, circuit, and task validators remain separate tickets.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-003_rationale.md:95:- merge this numerical execution surface into a full multi-layer Milestone 13\nagent_tickets/milestone_7_synapse_coupling_tickets.md:17:The repo currently stops at per-neuron geometry and operator bundles plus an aggregated connectivity registry. Milestone 7 needs a first-class handoff contract for synapse-level data and inter-neuron coupling artifacts, but there is no canonical definition for where synapse-derived assets live, how downstream code discovers them, how coupling topology is encoded, or how sign, delay, aggregation, and morphology fallback decisions are documented. Without a versioned contract and a decisive design note, later simulator and UI work will bind itself to ad hoc filenames, undocumented semantics, and incompatible assumptions about what a \"coupling edge\" means.\nagent_tickets/milestone_7_synapse_coupling_tickets.md:147:Even if the Milestone 7 build tickets land individually, the repo still needs one explicit integration pass that verifies the pieces work together as a coherent synapse-to-coupling pipeline. Without a dedicated verification ticket, it is too easy to stop at local success on isolated subtasks while leaving behind contract drift, partial manifest updates, broken inspection paths, weak regression coverage, or mismatches between synapse ingestion, anchor mapping, coupling assembly, and the documentation that later simulator milestones will rely on.\nagent_tickets/milestone_7_synapse_coupling_tickets.md:154:- The verification pass checks contract compatibility across the synapse registry, anchor mapping artifacts, coupling bundles, inspection tooling, manifest discovery, and fallback behavior for mixed morphology classes.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:1:# FW-M13-006 Rationale\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:6:left a gap at the task-validation layer. This ticket adds the missing\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:7:task-sanity execution surface in `flywire_wave.validation_task`.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:12:- are task-level outputs stable across the declared seed inventory\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:19:  `run_task_validation_suite` accepts either a loaded experiment-analysis\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:21:  Milestone 13 validation bundle artifacts.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:22:- The manifest workflow stays bundle-oriented instead of re-running task\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:24:  `execute_task_validation_workflow` resolves the normalized Milestone 13 plan,\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:29:  The suite records shared-comparison inventory, task-decoder inventory, and\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:33:  Missing seed rows, missing perturbation variants, missing task-decoder\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:47:make task-validate \\\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:56:That target runs `scripts/26_task_validation.py`, resolves the task-only\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:58:standard Milestone 13 bundle layout.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:63:from flywire_wave.validation_task import (\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:64:    execute_task_validation_workflow,\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:65:    run_task_validation_suite,\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:73:- `tests/test_validation_task.py` materializes the existing Milestone 12\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:74:  comparison fixture, augments the readout-analysis plan with task-decoder\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:77:- The same test file exercises the end-to-end task workflow with clean and\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:81:  perturbation variants, missing task seed coverage, and missing task-decoder\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:90:- The first version evaluates only the task-level signals already exposed by the\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:92:  It does not introduce a second task-analysis kernel or a new downstream\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-006_rationale.md:108:- add explicit support for more perturbation families once Milestone 13 starts\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:1:# FW-M13-005 Rationale\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:5:Milestone 13 still lacked a circuit-sanity execution surface even after the\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:6:taxonomy, planning, numerical checks, and morphology checks landed. This ticket\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:7:adds that missing layer in `flywire_wave.validation_circuit`.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:9:The first circuit suite covers four concrete questions:\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:19:- One library-owned suite handles both motif probes and small-circuit checks.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:20:  `run_circuit_validation_suite` accepts reusable delay, sign, aggregation, and\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:21:  motion-pathway case objects, then writes the standard Milestone 13 validation\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:32:  `compute_shared_readout_analysis`, so circuit findings line up with the same\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:35:  `execute_circuit_validation_workflow` discovers local simulator bundles,\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:40:  surface-wave-versus-baseline arm pair, which keeps the first circuit suite\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:50:The repo now exposes one small-circuit command path:\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:53:make circuit-validate \\\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:59:That target runs `scripts/25_circuit_validation.py`, reuses local simulator\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:61:standard Milestone 13 validation artifacts under the deterministic validation\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:68:from flywire_wave.validation_circuit import run_circuit_validation_suite\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:78:- `tests/test_validation_circuit.py` drives the reusable suite directly with\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:82:- The same test file runs the small-circuit workflow on a local\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:87:This keeps the first circuit suite local, deterministic, and fast enough for\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-005_rationale.md:99:  sufficiency remains a reviewer decision in the standard Milestone 13 handoff.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-004_rationale.md:1:# FW-M13-004 Rationale\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-004_rationale.md:5:Milestone 13 needed a first morphology-sanity execution surface that can say\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-004_rationale.md:8:`flywire_wave.validation_morphology`.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-004_rationale.md:26:  `run_morphology_validation_suite` accepts local probe cases, geometry trace\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-004_rationale.md:34:  morphology-only simulator.\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-004_rationale.md:43:  When callers do not pass explicit `reference_root_specs`, the morphology\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-004_rationale.md:50:The repo now exposes one local command path for morphology sanity:\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-004_rationale.md:53:make morphology-validate CONFIG=path/to/config.yaml MANIFEST=path/to/manifest.yaml\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-004_rationale.md:60:make morphology-validate \\\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-004_rationale.md:69:.venv/bin/python -m unittest tests.test_validation_morphology -v\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-004_rationale.md:78:- `tests/test_validation_morphology.py` drives the local probe suite with\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-004_rationale.md:93:  surface-wave result bundles and do not invent a separate morphology-input\ndocs/validation_ladder_notes/FW-M13-004_rationale.md:106:- expand manifest-owned morphology checks once Milestone 12 experiment-analysis\ndocs/simulator_result_bundle_design.md:35:  single-compartment neurons on the same selected circuit with the same shared\ndocs/simulator_result_bundle_design.md:58:- surface-localized inputs on explicit morphology regions\ndocs/simulator_result_bundle_design.md:59:- morphology-bound propagation state\ndocs/simulator_result_bundle_design.md:141:- wave-only morphology/state details live under `extensions/` and do not\nsrc/flywire_wave/milestone11_readiness.py:50:from .hybrid_morphology_contract import (\nsrc/flywire_wave/milestone11_readiness.py:56:from .hybrid_morphology_runtime import (\nsrc/flywire_wave/milestone11_readiness.py:98:    discover_simulator_root_morphology_metadata,\nsrc/flywire_wave/milestone11_readiness.py:113:    \"tests.test_hybrid_morphology_contract\",\nsrc/flywire_wave/milestone11_readiness.py:114:    \"tests.test_hybrid_morphology_runtime\",\nsrc/flywire_wave/milestone11_readiness.py:358:            \"skeleton->point, and point->surface loop. Broader morphology-specific approximation \"\nsrc/flywire_wave/milestone11_readiness.py:369:            \"incident mixed-class coupling assets remains a follow-on engineering task.\"\nsrc/flywire_wave/milestone11_readiness.py:620:        realized