r(patch_graph_path),\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T185349Z/FW-M6-001_Freeze_a_versioned_operator_bundle_contract_and_discretization_design_note/stdout.jsonl:33:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_16\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '470,560p' docs/milestones.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"- identifying which geometric descriptors matter for propagation  \\n- defining acceptable error bounds for coarse geometry\\n\\n### Done when\\n\\n- active neurons have consistent geometry assets  \\n- simplification is automated and reproducible  \\n- raw vs simplified vs patchified geometry can be visualized together\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Milestone 6 — Construct surface discretizations and operators\\n\\n**Workload split:** Math/physics-heavy  \\n**Suggested lead:** Grant  \\n**Implementation support:** Jack\\n\\n### Goal\\n\\nTurn neuron surfaces into simulation-ready numerical objects.\\n\\n### Build\\n\\n- adjacency structures  \\n- geodesic neighborhoods  \\n- graph or cotangent Laplacian  \\n- patch graph  \\n- local tangent frames  \\n- boundary masks  \\n- optional anisotropy tensors  \\n- fine-to-coarse transfer operators\\n\\n### Agent implements:\\n\\n- sparse matrix construction code  \\n- asset serialization  \\n- performance optimization  \\n- operator test harnesses  \\n- visualization of operator outputs on meshes\\n\\n### Agent researches and weighs options, chooses best, implements and documents all reasoning in a mark down file:\\n\\n- choosing the correct discretization family  \\n- deciding whether to use graph-based or mesh-based operators  \\n- specifying stability-relevant properties  \\n- defining what should be conserved or damped  \\n- checking whether the operator is faithful enough to the intended physics\\n\\n### Done when\\n\\n- a pulse can be initialized on a single neuron  \\n- propagation on the surface is numerically stable  \\n- coarse and fine operators can be compared  \\n- operator quality metrics exist\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Milestone 7 — Map synapses and define inter-neuron coupling\\n\\n**Workload split:** Shared, leaning math/physics  \\n**Suggested lead:** Shared\\n\\n### Goal\\n\\nTurn connectome edges into transfers between neuron surface states.\\n\\n### Need to define\\n\\n- where synaptic input lands on the receiving surface  \\n- where output is read on the presynaptic neuron  \\n- whether coupling is:  \\n  - point-to-point  \\n  - patch-to-patch  \\n  - distributed patch cloud  \\n- how synaptic sign and delay are handled  \\n- how multiple synapses aggregate\\n\\n### Jack owns\\n\\n- synapse table processing  \\n- locating nearest patches / skeleton nodes  \\n- building fast lookup structures  \\n- serializing coupling maps  \\n- coupling inspection tools\\n\\n### Grant owns\\n\\n- defining coupling kernels  \\n- choosing delay models  \\n- deciding how synaptic transfer modifies the surface state  \\n- determining whether coupling is instantaneous, filtered, nonlinear, etc.\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T185349Z/FW-M6-001_Freeze_a_versioned_operator_bundle_contract_and_discretization_design_note/stdout.jsonl:39:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_19\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,220p' docs/geometry_descriptor_qa.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# Geometry Descriptors And QA Budgets\\n\\nMilestone 5 now writes two sidecars per processed morphology bundle:\\n\\n- `<root_id>_descriptors.json`: cheap derived summaries for the raw mesh, simplified mesh, coarse patch graph, and optional skeleton\\n- `<root_id>_qa.json`: thresholded comparisons that turn those summaries into pass, warn, or fail outcomes\\n\\nThis note documents the first descriptor set and the default budgets so later\\nMilestone 6 operator work and Milestone 11 hybrid-morphology work have a shared\\nbaseline for what currently counts as an acceptable approximation.\\n\\n## Why these descriptors exist\\n\\nThe first pass stays deliberately pragmatic:\\n\\n- counts: vertices, faces, edges, patch count, skeleton nodes, segments\\n- component structure: connected-component counts plus largest-component fractions\\n- size and extent: surface area, optional watertight volume, axis-aligned bounds, extents, centroid\\n- local scale proxies: mean / median / max surface edge length\\n- coarse occupancy: patch-size statistics, dominant-patch fraction, singleton-patch fraction, centroid extent coverage, surface-vertex coverage ratio\\n- skeleton summary: cable length, branch points, leaves, roots, bounds, extent\\n\\nThese metrics are cheap to compute locally, stable enough for regression tests,\\nand easy to explain. They do not try to prove physical equivalence. They answer\\nthe narrower Milestone 5 question: did the asset builder preserve gross\\nconnectivity, length scales, and occupancy well enough to justify later,\\nmore-specific numerical checks?\\n\\n## Default QA budgets\\n\\nThe build currently evaluates these thresholds from `meshing.qa_thresholds`:\\n\\n| Metric | Default warn | Default fail | Blocking by default | Rationale |\\n| --- | ---: | ---: | :---: | --- |\\n| `simplified_component_count_delta` | disabled | `0.0` | yes | Simplification should not create or remove connected pieces. |\\n| `simplified_surface_area_rel_error` | `0.15` | `0.30` | yes | Gross area drift changes membrane-scale operator weights. |\\n| `simplified_extent_rel_error_max` | `0.10` | `0.20` | yes | Large extent drift changes propagation length scales. |\\n| `simplified_centroid_shift_fraction_of_diagonal` | `0.05` | `0.10` | no | Useful distortion signal, but not a hard blocker by itself. |\\n| `simplified_volume_rel_error` | `0.20` | `0.40` | no | Informative only when both meshes are watertight. |\\n| `coarse_component_count_delta` | disabled | `0.0` | yes | Patch graph connectivity should match the simplified surface. |\\n| `coarse_surface_vertex_coverage_gap` | disabled | `0.0` | yes | Every simplified vertex must map to a patch. |\\n| `coarse_max_patch_vertex_fraction` | `0.60` | `0.80` | no | Warn when one coarse patch dominates most of the surface. |\\n| `coarse_singleton_patch_fraction` | `0.25` | `0.50` | no | Warn when patchification fragments into too many singletons. |\\n\\n`disabled` means the default profile has no warning band for that metric and\\nonly treats non-zero drift as a failure.\\n\\n## Blocking vs non-blocking\\n\\nThe QA sidecar can record `fail` for both blocking and non-blocking metrics.\\nThe build script only exits non-zero when a failed check is marked\\n`blocking: true`.\\n\\nCurrent intent:\\n\\n- blocking: topological integrity and obvious gross geometry drift that would\\n  invalidate downstream operator construction\\n- non-blocking: review signals that should be surfaced to humans but may still\\n  produce usable artifacts for exploratory work\\n\\nTeams can tighten or relax the budgets per config without changing code.\\n\\n## Expected follow-up work\\n\\nMilestone 6 will likely add operator-aware checks such as Laplacian-spectrum\\ndrift, geodesic path distortion, or transfer-operator residuals. Milestone 11\\nmay promote the skeleton summary from descriptive metadata to representation\\nselection logic. This document only claims a baseline, not completeness.\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T185349Z/FW-M6-001_Freeze_a_versioned_operator_bundle_contract_and_discretization_design_note/stdout.jsonl:109:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_66\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"nl -ba docs/operator_bundle_design.md | sed -n '1,220p'\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"     1\\t# Milestone 6 Operator Bundle Contract And Discretization Choice\\n     2\\t\\n     3\\tThis note freezes the first operator-facing contract for Milestone 6 so later\\n     4\\tsimulator work can target explicit archive roles and explicit numerical\\n     5\\tassumptions instead of reverse-engineering Milestone 5 geometry bundles.\\n     6\\t\\n     7\\t## Contract summary\\n     8\\t\\n     9\\tThe processed manifest now carries `_operator_contract_version:\\n    10\\toperator_bundle.v1` plus a per-root `operator_bundle` block. That block owns:\\n    11\\t\\n    12\\t- the fine operator archive\\n    13\\t- the coarse operator archive\\n    14\\t- the transfer-operator archive\\n    15\\t- the operator metadata sidecar\\n    16\\t- the realized discretization family and fallback status\\n    17\\t- normalization / mass treatment\\n    18\\t- boundary-condition mode\\n    19\\t- geodesic-neighborhood settings\\n    20\\t- transfer-operator availability\\n    21\\t\\n    22\\tCompatibility during migration is deliberate:\\n    23\\t\\n    24\\t- `fine_operator` is currently a manifest alias to the legacy\\n    25\\t  `surface_graph_path`\\n    26\\t- `coarse_operator` is currently a manifest alias to the legacy\\n    27\\t  `patch_graph_path`\\n    28\\t- the legacy `<root_id>_meta.json` sidecar is still written so Milestone 5\\n    29\\t  consumers do not break while downstream code migrates to the new contract\\n    30\\t\\n    31\\t## Candidate families\\n    32\\t\\n    33\\t### Graph-based surface operators\\n    34\\t\\n    35\\tDefinition:\\n    36\\t\\n    37\\t- surface adjacency from the simplified mesh connectivity\\n    38\\t- combinatorial or normalized graph Laplacian\\n    39\\t- patch transfers built from patch membership only\\n    40\\t\\n    41\\tAdvantages:\\n    42\\t\\n    43\\t- robust on imperfect meshes\\n    44\\t- cheap to build and easy to regression test\\n    45\\t- no dependence on cotangent-weight edge cases\\n    46\\t\\n    47\\tCosts:\\n    48\\t\\n    49\\t- ignores triangle geometry and surface area unless extra weighting is added\\n    50\\t- geodesic distance is only approximated by hop count\\n    51\\t- boundary semantics are implicit and easy to misinterpret\\n    52\\t- convergence to a surface PDE is weaker than for a metric-aware mesh operator\\n    53\\t\\n    54\\t### Mesh-based operators\\n    55\\t\\n    56\\tDefinition:\\n    57\\t\\n    58\\t- triangle-mesh Laplace-Beltrami discretization on the simplified surface\\n    59\\t- cotangent stiffness matrix\\n    60\\t- explicit mass matrix\\n    61\\t- coarse operators derived from fine operators and transfer maps\\n    62\\t\\n    63\\tAdvantages:\\n    64\\t\\n    65\\t- metric-aware and standard for diffusion / wave equations on surfaces\\n    66\\t- makes conservation and stability statements precise in a mesh inner product\\n    67\\t- clean boundary interpretation when seams or open surfaces exist\\n    68\\t- gives a principled path to Galerkin coarse operators\\n    69\\t\\n    70\\tCosts:\\n    71\\t\\n    72\\t- requires handling degenerate triangles, non-manifold cases, and negative\\n    73\\t  cotangent edge contributions carefully\\n    74\\t- more implementation work than a graph Laplacian\\n    75\\t\\n    76\\t## Decision\\n    77\\t\\n    78\\tThe default fine-surface discretization for Milestone 6 is:\\n    79\\t\\n    80\\t- `triangle_mesh_cotangent_fem`\\n    81\\t- lumped mass matrix\\n    82\\t- mass-normalized state inner product\\n    83\\t- zero-flux boundary handling on the simplified closed surface\\n    84\\t\\n    85\\tThis is the default the later wave engine should treat as scientifically\\n    86\\tauthoritative.\\n    87\\t\\n    88\\tThe default coarse construction is:\\n    89\\t\\n    90\\t- fine-to-coarse restriction by lumped-mass patch averaging\\n    91\\t- coarse-to-fine prolongation by piecewise-constant patch injection\\n    92\\t- coarse operator by Galerkin projection from the fine operator\\n    93\\t\\n    94\\tThis keeps the fine and coarse systems comparable in one inner product instead\\n    95\\tof treating the patch graph as an unrelated second discretization.\\n    96\\t\\n    97\\t## Allowed fallback\\n    98\\t\\n    99\\tFallback is allowed when the default operator cannot be serialized safely or has\\n   100\\tnot been built yet. The allowed fallback family is:\\n   101\\t\\n   102\\t- `surface_graph_uniform_laplacian`\\n   103\\t- counting-measure / uniform-vertex averaging on transfers\\n   104\\t- geodesic neighborhoods represented by surface-graph hop counts\\n   105\\t\\n   106\\tUse the fallback only when at least one of these is true:\\n   107\\t\\n   108\\t1. the simplified mesh has degeneracies or topology issues that make cotangent\\n   109\\t   assembly unreliable\\n   110\\t2. a build is intentionally limited to the Milestone 5 geometry bundle plus\\n   111\\t   structural transfer data\\n   112\\t3. a regression fixture needs a deterministic structural operator without the\\n   113\\t   full metric machinery\\n   114\\t\\n   115\\tWhenever fallback is used, the manifest must say so explicitly through the\\n   116\\tper-root `operator_bundle.discretization_family`, `mass_treatment`,\\n   117\\t`normalization`, and `realization_mode` fields.\\n   118\\t\\n   119\\t## Conserved and damped quantities\\n   120\\t\\n   121\\tThe later wave engine inherits these expectations:\\n   122\\t\\n   123\\t- the constant field remains in the nullspace of the Laplacian\\n   124\\t- zero-flux boundaries do not inject or remove net mass\\n   125\\t- pure diffusion should dissipate energy and preserve total mass\\n   126\\t- undamped wave propagation should not gain energy from the spatial operator\\n   127\\t- any damping operator must be positive semidefinite and separate from the\\n   128\\t  conservative spatial operator\\n   129\\t- fine/coarse restriction and prolongation should preserve constants; no\\n   130\\t  transfer step should create a net source term by itself\\n   131\\t\\n   132\\t## Stability-relevant assumptions\\n   133\\t\\n   134\\tLater milestones should preserve these assumptions instead of silently changing\\n   135\\tthem:\\n   136\\t\\n   137\\t- stiffness operators are symmetric\\n   138\\t- mass operators are positive diagonal after lumping\\n   139\\t- the effective generalized operator is positive semidefinite\\n   140\\t- boundary treatment stays zero-flux unless an experiment explicitly opts into\\n   141\\t  absorbing or clamped boundaries\\n   142\\t- time-step limits should be derived from the largest relevant eigenvalue of\\n   143\\t  `M^{-1}L` rather than an ad hoc graph-degree rule\\n   144\\t- coarse operators and transfer maps should be interpreted in the same inner\\n   145\\t  product as the fine operator\\n   146\\t\\n   147\\t## What the current bundle guarantees\\n   148\\t\\n   149\\t`operator_bundle.v1` lands before the full cotangent implementation. The\\n   150\\tcurrent repository therefore serializes:\\n   151\\t\\n   152\\t- a fine operator alias through the legacy surface-graph archive\\n   153\\t- a coarse operator alias through the legacy patch-graph archive\\n   154\\t- an explicit transfer-operator archive for coarse/fine discovery\\n   155\\t- an operator metadata sidecar that records the realized fallback mode\\n   156\\t\\n   157\\tThat is intentional. The contract is frozen now so later tickets can upgrade the\\n   158\\tnumerics without renegotiating filenames, manifest keys, or the default\\n   159\\tstability assumptions.\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\ndocs/validation_ladder_design.md:5:Milestone 13 needs one contract-owned validation vocabulary before validator\ndocs/validation_ladder_design.md:16:  numerical warnings and local stability review.\ndocs/validation_ladder_design.md:22:Milestone 13 therefore layers validation on top of those contract-owned\ndocs/validation_ladder_design.md:31:- `numerical_sanity` -> `numerical_stability`\ndocs/validation_ladder_design.md:35:- `morphology_sanity` -> `morphology_dependence`\ndocs/validation_ladder_design.md:39:- `circuit_sanity` -> `circuit_response`\ndocs/validation_ladder_design.md:43:- `task_sanity` -> `task_effect_reproducibility`\ndocs/validation_ladder_design.md:46:  `task_decoder_robustness`\ndocs/validation_ladder_design.md:49:Milestone 13 work may add execution code or more validators, but it must not\ndocs/validation_ladder_design.md:66:- numerical validators start from Milestone 6 and Milestone 10 review artifacts\ndocs/validation_ladder_design.md:68:- morphology validators use Milestone 11 mixed-fidelity inspection plus the\ndocs/validation_ladder_design.md:70:- circuit and task validators stay on the shared simulator-result and packaged\ndocs/validation_ladder_design.md:134:Later Milestone 13 workflows should discover these paths through\ndocs/validation_ladder_design.md:137:## Invariants For Later Milestone 13 Tickets\ndocs/validation_ladder_design.md:143:- `validation_ladder.v1` remains the canonical source of Milestone 13 layer,\nsrc/flywire_wave/experiment_comparison_analysis.py:64:from .task_decoder_analysis import (\nsrc/flywire_wave/experiment_comparison_analysis.py:66:    compute_task_decoder_analysis,\nsrc/flywire_wave/experiment_comparison_analysis.py:270:    task_metric_ids = sorted(\nsrc/flywire_wave/experiment_comparison_analysis.py:296:    task_result = (\nsrc/flywire_wave/experiment_comparison_analysis.py:297:        compute_task_decoder_analysis(\nsrc/flywire_wave/experiment_comparison_analysis.py:300:                metric_ids=task_metric_ids,\nsrc/flywire_wave/experiment_comparison_analysis.py:304:        if task_metric_ids\nsrc/flywire_wave/experiment_comparison_analysis.py:335:        task_result=task_result,\nsrc/flywire_wave/experiment_comparison_analysis.py:384:        task_result=task_result,\nsrc/flywire_wave/experiment_comparison_analysis.py:388:    task_scores, task_score_families = _build_task_scores(\nsrc/flywire_wave/experiment_comparison_analysis.py:392:    task_scores.sort(key=_task_score_sort_key)\nsrc/flywire_wave/experiment_comparison_analysis.py:393:    task_sco